     168                 :             : 
     169                 :             : // Coefficient scaling and quantization with AV1 TX are tailored to
     170                 :             : // the AV1 TX transforms.  Regardless of the bit-depth of the input,
     171                 :             : // the transform stages scale the coefficient values up by a factor of
     172                 :             : // 8 (3 bits) over the scale of the pixel values.  Thus, for 8-bit
     173                 :             : // input, the coefficients have effectively 11 bits of scale depth
     174                 :             : // (8+3), 10-bit input pixels result in 13-bit coefficient depth
     175                 :             : // (10+3) and 12-bit pixels yield 15-bit (12+3) coefficient depth.
     176                 :             : // All quantizers are built using this invariant of x8, 3-bit scaling,
     177                 :             : // thus the Q3 suffix.
     178                 :             : 
     179                 :             : // A partial exception to this rule is large transforms; to avoid
     180                 :             : // overflow, TX blocks with > 256 pels (>16x16) are scaled only
     181                 :             : // 4-times unity (2 bits) over the pixel depth, and TX blocks with
     182                 :             : // over 1024 pixels (>32x32) are scaled up only 2x unity (1 bit).
     183                 :             : // This descaling is found via av1_tx_get_scale().  Thus, 16x32, 32x16
     184                 :             : // and 32x32 transforms actually return Q2 coefficients, and 32x64,
     185                 :             : // 64x32 and 64x64 transforms return Q1 coefficients.  However, the
     186                 :             : // quantizers are de-scaled down on-the-fly by the same amount
     187                 :             : // (av1_tx_get_scale()) during quantization, and as such the
     188                 :             : // dequantized/decoded coefficients, even for large TX blocks, are always
     189                 :             : // effectively Q3. Meanwhile, quantized/coded coefficients are Q0
     190                 :             : // because Qn quantizers are applied to Qn tx coefficients.
     191                 :             : 
     192                 :             : // Note that encoder decision making (which uses the quantizer to
     193                 :             : // generate several bespoke lamdas for RDO and other heuristics)
     194                 :             : // expects quantizers to be larger for higher-bitdepth input.  In
     195                 :             : // addition, the minimum allowable quantizer is 4; smaller values will
     196                 :             : // underflow to 0 in the actual quantization routines.
     197                 :             : 
     198                 :           0 : int16_t av1_dc_quant_QTX(int qindex, int delta, aom_bit_depth_t bit_depth) {
     199                 :           0 :   const int q_clamped = clamp(qindex + delta, 0, MAXQ);
     200                 :           0 :   switch (bit_depth) {
     201                 :           0 :     case AOM_BITS_8: return dc_qlookup_QTX[q_clamped];
     202                 :           0 :     case AOM_BITS_10: return dc_qlookup_10_QTX[q_clamped];
     203                 :           0 :     case AOM_BITS_12: return dc_qlookup_12_QTX[q_clamped];
     204                 :             :     default:
     205                 :             :       assert(0 && "bit_depth should be AOM_BITS_8, AOM_BITS_10 or AOM_BITS_12");
     206                 :           0 :       return -1;
     207                 :             :   }
     208                 :           0 : }
     209                 :             :
